{"schema_version":2,"id":"2712e970-60d6-497b-afdd-802dc4092dc9","timestamp":"2026-06-04T13:25:51.057149737+00:00","context":{"session_id":"68c950a0-f723-4516-9ab7-4b2d56ea1ec6","turn_id":"840984ca-b594-42d8-899c-3f30aff7c88f","turn_index":5,"protocol_iteration":0,"effect_id":"2","llm_call_id":"68c950a0-f723-4516-9ab7-4b2d56ea1ec6:5:0:0","metadata":{"replay_key":"68c950a0-f723-4516-9ab7-4b2d56ea1ec6:840984ca-b594-42d8-899c-3f30aff7c88f:5:0:llm_call:2"}},"type":"llm_call_started","request":{"model":"anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.6","model_variant":"high","messages":[{"role":"system","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":"You are an AI coding assistant piloting the lash harness.\n\n## Execution\n\n**All actions go through `lashlang`.** Invoke documented operations with module syntax like `await agents.spawn({ ... })?` or `await web.search({ ... })?` from inside a fenced `lashlang` block. Start from operations listed under **Showcased Tools**; if a discovery tool is available, use it to find additional module call forms before calling them. Emit a block whenever you need to call an available operation or compute a value. Plain prose is for direct conversational replies that need no action.\n\n### `print` vs `submit`\n\n- `print <expr>` — inspect a value and keep going. Output appears on the next step and is capped: keep full tool results in variables and print only lengths, selected fields, samples, or slices. Don't print large objects just to hand-copy IDs back into code.\n- `submit <expr>` — final answer; ends the turn. Strings pass through as the reply; other values render as pretty JSON. If a **Required output** schema is present, the value must match it.\n\nNever `submit` a raw tool-result dump. If you need to look at something, `print` it, then `submit` a summary on a later step.\n\n### Turn shape\n\n**Exactly one ` ```lashlang ` fenced block per response.** Anything after the first block closes is dropped. Only ` ```lashlang ` is recognised — `rlm` and other labels are treated as plain prose.\n\n- Write small blocks. Each should do one focused step.\n- Keep prose around the block to one or two sentences of reasoning. Don't describe an action in prose instead of executing it.\n- After each result, decide: another block (more work), or finish.\n\nExample — inspect with an available operation, then submit:\n\n````\nChecking the available data.\n\n```lashlang\nresult = await web.search({ query: \"value\" })?\nprint { summary: slice(to_string(result), 0, 200) }\n```\n````\n\n…then on the next turn, once you've seen what you need:\n\n````\n```lashlang\nsubmit \"The bound version is 0.2.61.\"\n```\n````\n\n\n### Language\n\n- Values: null, booleans, numbers, strings, lists, records, and immutable `Image` handles. Literals: `[a, b]`, `{ a: 1, b: 2 }`.\n- Images: image-producing tools may return an `Image` value. Read metadata with `.id`, `.label`, `.size`, `.width`, `.height`; fields are read-only. `print(image)` or `print` on a list/record containing images sends both descriptor text and the actual image attachment to the next model call. `submit(image)`, `to_string(image)`, and JSON-like serialization emit only `{ \"type\": \"image\", \"id\": ..., \"label\": ..., \"size\": ..., \"width\": ..., \"height\": ... }`. `len(image)` is invalid; use `.size`.\n- Strings: `\"...\"` supports `\\n`, `\\r`, `\\t`, `\\\"`, and `\\\\`; `\"\"\"...\"\"\"` is multiline with the same escapes; `r\"\"\"...\"\"\"` and `r'''...'''` are raw multiline strings and preserve content exactly. Use raw multiline strings for JSON, Markdown, and other payloads with braces, backslashes, quotes, heredocs, or `@@` hunk markers.\n- Assign with `name = expr`. Variables persist across fenced blocks within the turn. You can also update mutable collection paths rooted at a variable: `record.field = value`, `record[key] = value`, `list[i] = value`, and nested forms like `state.groups[g].count = count + 1`. Record field/index assignment inserts or replaces fields; list assignment replaces an existing integer index only. Record indexing reads dynamic string-coerced keys and returns `null` when missing, so histogram code can use `counts[g] = counts[g] + 1`.\n- Module operations: call host capabilities through documented lowercase module paths, e.g. `await agents.spawn({ task: task })?`, `await web.search({ query: q })?`, or `await gmail.work.send({ to: to, body: body })?`. Host operations are awaited effects; pure UpperCamel value constructors shown in the Host Surface are ordinary expressions and must not be awaited. Bare calls are builtins only, not tools. `?` aborts the block with sanitized operation metadata if the operation fails.\n- Sleep: pause foreground code or process code with `sleep for \"5s\"` or `sleep until deadline`. Durations accept milliseconds, `ms`, `s`, `m`, or `h`; deadlines accept RFC3339 text or Unix epoch milliseconds.\n- Background processes: `process name(param: TYPE) { ... }` declares a reusable process definition. `handle = start name(param: value)` creates one process run from that definition and returns its run handle; trigger activations also create process runs. For account-parametric work, pass typed module authorities explicitly, e.g. `process notify(mail: Gmail) { await mail.send({ body: body })? finish true }` and `start notify(mail: gmail.work)`. For one-off concrete automations, a process body may reference concrete host paths such as `agents`, `web`, or `gmail.work` directly; params and locals shadow those captures. Inside a process use `yield value`, `wake value`, `finish value`, `fail value`, `payload = wait signal`, or `signal run handle with payload`. `wake value` emits a `process.wake` event that notifies the agent/session with `value`; use it when process progress, trigger output, or other background work should re-enter the model as context. `finish value` completes the run and stores `value` as the process success value. `fail value` completes it as failed; falling off the end is `finish null`. `submit` and `print` are foreground-only and invalid inside processes. `await handle` waits and returns a result wrapper like `{ ok: true, value: ... }`; when you need fields from the `finish` value, use `result = (await handle)?` and then read `result.field`. Cancel a live run with `cancel handle` (best-effort). If the Host Surface includes `processes.list`, use `await processes.list({})?` for running runs, `await processes.list({ definition: name })?` for runs of a definition, and `await processes.list({ status: \"any\" })?` for visible run history.\n- Execution labels: use `@label(title: \"Label\")` or `@label(title: \"Label\", description: \"Details\")` to name important Lashlang phases and graph steps. At top level, label meaningful setup, resource calls, submissions, branches, loops, or process declarations. Inside a `process` body, label durable steps such as awaited module calls, `start`, `sleep`, `wait signal`, `signal run`, `wake`, `yield`, `finish`, `fail`, `if`, loops, and setup statements that explain the process. Titles/descriptions must be string literals; do not use variables, interpolation, icons, colors, layout hints, or extra keys.\n- Independent operation fanout: call independent operations directly and store their values, e.g. `a = await web.search({ query: \"one\" })?` and `b = await files.read({ path: \"notes/two.md\" })?`. Use a named process for multi-step background work.\n- Control flow: statement `if`/`for`/`while`; `break` exits the nearest loop; `continue` skips to the nearest loop's next iteration; expression ternary `cond ? yes : no` (there is no expression-form `if`); boolean negation via `!cond` or `not cond`. Prefer bounded `while` loops where possible and bounded `for` loops over ranges/lists for fill or retry logic. `submit` is different from `break`: it ends the whole program/turn.\n- Bare expressions are valid statements in normal blocks.\n- When a **Bound Variables** section appears in the prompt, those names are already in scope inside lashlang blocks — read them directly instead of restating their values.\n\n### Host Surface\n\nAwaited runtime operations:\n\n- `await board.play(any)? -> any`\n- `await board.read(any)? -> any`\n- `await control.continue_as(any)? -> any`\n- `await triggers.cancel({ handle: TriggerHandle<any> })? -> bool`\n- `await triggers.list({ target: Process<any, any>?, name: str?, source_type: str?, enabled: bool? })? -> list[TriggerRegistration]`\n- `await triggers.register({ source: dict, target: Process<any, any>, inputs: dict, name: str? })? -> TriggerHandle<any>`\n\n### Builtins\n\nCall as functions (e.g. `len(x)`, `slice(s, 0, 200)`). For `slice`, `null` bounds mean start/end; negative bounds count from the end.\n\n- `len(x)` — length of string/list/record (0 for null); use `image.size` for images\n- `empty(x)` — true if length is 0\n- `slice(s, start, end)` — substring or sublist\n- `range(end)` / `range(start, end)` / `range(start, end, step)` — integer list, end-exclusive; positive or negative `step`, never `0`\n- `ceil_div(a, b)` / `floor_div(a, b)` — integer division helpers for chunk/count math; divisor must not be `0`\n- `push(list, item)` — new list with one item appended\n- `split(s, sep)` / `join(list, sep)` — string split/join\n- `find(s, needle, start?)` — zero-based character index of the first literal match, or `null`; `start` defaults to `0` and is a non-negative character index; an empty `needle` returns `start` when it is in bounds\n- `grep_text(s, needle)` — literal in-memory line search; `needle` must be non-empty; returns one record per matching line: `{ line: int, text: str, match: str, start: int, end: int }`, where `line` is 1-based, `text` is the line without its line ending, and `start`/`end` are zero-based character offsets within that line's `text` with `end` exclusive\n- `trim(s)` — strip whitespace\n- `starts_with(s, prefix)` / `ends_with(s, suffix)` / `contains(haystack, needle)`\n- `keys(record)` / `values(record)`\n- `to_string(x)` / `to_int(x)` / `to_float(x)`\n- `json_parse(s)` — parse a JSON string into a value\n- `format(template, arg0, arg1, ...)` — positional interpolation: `{}` auto-numbers, `{0}` / `{1}` pick a specific arg, `{{` / `}}` escape literal braces. Do not wrap args in a list: use `format(\"It is {}.\", trim(now.output))`, not `format(\"It is {}.\", [trim(now.output)])`.\n- `validate(value, Type { ... })` — check an intermediate value against a Type literal and return it unchanged, or abort with a validation error\n\n\n### Common patterns\n\nOperation-level errors are different from successful results that contain domain errors. `?` aborts the block only when the module operation itself failed:\n\n```lashlang\nprobe = await web.search({ query: \"value\" })?\nsubmit probe\n```\n\nBuild collections with explicit loops, not comprehensions:\n\n```lashlang\nitems = []\nfor key in [\"a\", \"b\"] {\n  value = await web.search({ query: key })?\n  items = push(items, { key: key, value: value })\n}\nsubmit items\n```\n\nPrint narrow observations. Keep large values in variables and print only keys, lengths, selected fields, or slices:\n\n```lashlang\nresult = await web.search({ query: \"value\" })?\ntext = to_string(result)\nprint { chars: len(text), head: slice(text, 0, 1200) }\n```\n\nFor multi-step work, inspect intermediate results before submitting success. Reaching `submit` ends the turn even mid-block:\n\n```lashlang\nfirst = await web.search({ query: \"value\" })?\nsecond = await web.fetch({ url: first[0].url })?\nif contains(to_string(second), \"needs_more_work\") {\n  print { first: first, second: second }\n} else {\n  submit second\n}\n```\n\n\n### Type literals\n\n`Type { field: shape, ... }` describes a record shape. Field separators are commas (trailing comma OK).\n\n- Scalars: `str`, `int`, `float`, `bool`, `dict`, `any`, `null`.\n- Collections: `list[shape]`, `enum[\"a\", \"b\"]`, nested `Type { ... }`.\n- **Optional field** — put `?` after the type: `email: str?` means the field may be absent from the record. If the field IS present, its value must be a string; `null` is **not** allowed.\n- **Nullable field** — use a union with `null`: `email: str | null` means the field is required and its value is either a string or null.\n- **Unions** — `a | b | c`, e.g. `status: str | int`, `value: str | null`.\n- Nested shapes require the `Type` keyword: `nested: Type { ok: bool }` (bare `{ ok: bool }` is rejected — that's a record value, not a type).\n\n```lashlang\nprofile = validate(record, Type { name: str, email: str?, tags: list[str] })\n```\n\n\n### Working with context\n\nYour turn's REPL trace is your working memory. Keep it small, decision-sized, and current. Big artifacts (files, search results, long pages, raw tool dumps) live outside — pull them in only when you need to compute over them yourself. Keep full results in variables; `print` only lengths, keys, selected fields, or slices, never large objects you intend to hand-copy IDs from.\n\nChoose the lightest mechanism that preserves progress:\n\n- Current variables already hold what you need → reason inline in lashlang.\n- Several independent operations are needed -> call each module operation and keep the values in variables; use a named `process` for multi-step background work.\n- The trace is bloated, stale, or failed attempts dominate -> use an available continuation tool to switch to a fresh AgentFrame with concrete state.\n- Anything tool-specific (parameters, return shapes, lifecycle) lives under **Showcased Tools** — don't infer a tool exists from these generic examples.\n\nExample fanout to two available operations (use `?` for fail-fast unwrapping):\n\n```lashlang\na = await web.search({ query: \"one\" })?\nb = await files.read({ path: \"notes/two.md\" })?\none = a\ntwo = b\nsubmit [one, two]\n```\n\n### Showcased Tools\n\n### await board.play({ cell: int >= 0 <= 8 })? -> record\nPlay one O move for the agent when it is O's turn. The move is a zero-based cell index: 0 top-left, 1 top-middle, 2 top-right, 3 middle-left, 4 center, 5 middle-right, 6 bottom-left, 7 bottom-middle, 8 bottom-right.\nParameters:\n- `cell: int >= 0 <= 8`\n\n### await board.read({})? -> record\nRead the app-owned Tic Tac Toe board. Returns the 0..8 index map, current marks by index, legal moves, winner, and whose turn it is.\n\n## Guidance\n\n- Be concise. Avoid filler, hedging, and performative tone.\n- Do not restate a conclusion you already stated. Once a fix location is identified, act on it in the same turn.\n- Prefer the simplest correct solution over cleverness or unnecessary abstraction.\n\n### Bound Variables\n\nThese variables are already bound in lashlang. Access them directly in fenced `lashlang` code; do not recreate them manually.\nType and size hints help you plan before inspecting a value.\n\nAvailable variables:\n- `history`: `list<HistoryItem>`, Readonly: true, projected binding, 13 entries\n\n## Environment\n\n### Tic Tac Toe Board\n\nYou are O. The human is X.\nCurrent turn: O.\nIndex map:\n0 top-left | 1 top-middle | 2 top-right\n3 middle-left | 4 center | 5 middle-right\n6 bottom-left | 7 bottom-middle | 8 bottom-right\nCurrent marks by index:\n0: X, 1: X, 2: O, 3: O, 4: O, 5: X, 6: X, 7: O, 8: X\nVisual board:\nX X O\nO O X\nX O X\nLegal moves: []\nStatus: draw.\nIf it is O's turn and the game is not over, call `board.play(...)` exactly once before answering. Only choose one of the legal move indexes. Use `board.read(...)` only when needed. Finish with `submit \"<one short user-facing sentence>\"`; do not repeat that sentence as prose outside the lashlang block. If your move ended the game, clearly say that you won or that the game ended in a draw; otherwise say it is the human's turn. Do not explain your strategy, do not describe threats, do not print an ASCII board, do not narrate every cell, and do not return JSON to the user."}]},{"role":"user","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":"--- history[0] · user message · 27 chars ---\n\nI played X in the top left."}]},{"role":"user","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":"--- history[1] · tool_call · play_move · ok · 1 ms ---\n\nArguments (15 chars):\n{\n  \"cell\": 4\n}\n\nResult (699 chars):\n{\n  \"accepted\": true,\n  \"board\": {\n    \"cells\": [\n      \"X\",\n      null,\n      null,\n      null,\n      \"O\",\n      null,\n      null,\n      null,\n      null\n    ],\n    \"index_map\": [\n      \"0 top-left\",\n      \"1 top-middle\",\n      \"2 top-right\",\n      \"3 middle-left\",\n      \"4 center\",\n      \"5 middle-right\",\n      \"6 bottom-left\",\n      \"7 bottom-middle\",\n      \"8 bottom-right\"\n    ],\n    \"legal_moves\": [\n      1,\n      2,\n      3,\n      5,\n      6,\n      7,\n      8\n    ],\n    \"marks_by_index\": \"0: X, 1: empty, 2: empty, 3: empty, 4: O, 5: empty, 6: empty, 7: empty, 8: empty\",\n    \"status\": \"X to move\",\n    \"turn\": \"X\",\n    \"winner\": null\n  },\n  \"move\": {\n    \"cell\": 4,\n    \"mark\": \"O\"\n  }\n}"}]},{"role":"assistant","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":""}]},{"role":"assistant","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":"--- history[3] · rlm step · protocol_iteration 0 ---\n\nReasoning (108 chars):\nI need to play O. X is at position 0 (top-left). The best strategic move is to take the center (position 4).\n\nCode:\n```lashlang\nresult = await board.play({ cell: 4 })?\nsubmit \"I've taken the center — your turn!\"\n```\n\nFinal output:\n\"I've taken the center — your turn!\""}]},{"role":"user","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":"--- history[4] · user message · 30 chars ---\n\nI played X in the bottom left."}]},{"role":"user","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":"--- history[5] · tool_call · play_move · ok · 1 ms ---\n\nArguments (15 chars):\n{\n  \"cell\": 3\n}\n\nResult (671 chars):\n{\n  \"accepted\": true,\n  \"board\": {\n    \"cells\": [\n      \"X\",\n      null,\n      null,\n      \"O\",\n      \"O\",\n      null,\n      \"X\",\n      null,\n      null\n    ],\n    \"index_map\": [\n      \"0 top-left\",\n      \"1 top-middle\",\n      \"2 top-right\",\n      \"3 middle-left\",\n      \"4 center\",\n      \"5 middle-right\",\n      \"6 bottom-left\",\n      \"7 bottom-middle\",\n      \"8 bottom-right\"\n    ],\n    \"legal_moves\": [\n      1,\n      2,\n      5,\n      7,\n      8\n    ],\n    \"marks_by_index\": \"0: X, 1: empty, 2: empty, 3: O, 4: O, 5: empty, 6: X, 7: empty, 8: empty\",\n    \"status\": \"X to move\",\n    \"turn\": \"X\",\n    \"winner\": null\n  },\n  \"move\": {\n    \"cell\": 3,\n    \"mark\": \"O\"\n  }\n}"}]},{"role":"assistant","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":""}]},{"role":"assistant","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":"--- history[7] · rlm step · protocol_iteration 0 ---\n\nReasoning (463 chars):\nX is at 0 (top-left) and 6 (bottom-left). O is at 4 (center). X has a potential threat along the left column (0, 3, 6) - wait, X has 0 and 6, so X could win with 3 (middle-left). I need to block at 3.\n\nBut wait, let me also think about winning moves. O is at 4 (center). Can I win? O only has one piece at 4, so no immediate win.\n\nI need to block X at 3 (middle-left) to prevent X from winning with 0, 3, 6.X threatens the left column (0, 3, 6) — must block at 3.\n\nCode:\n```lashlang\nresult = await board.play({ cell: 3 })?\nsubmit \"Your turn!\"\n```\n\nFinal output:\n\"Your turn!\""}]},{"role":"user","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":"--- history[8] · user message · 31 chars ---\n\nI played X in the middle right."}]},{"role":"user","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":"--- history[9] · tool_call · play_move · ok · 1 ms ---\n\nArguments (15 chars):\n{\n  \"cell\": 7\n}\n\nResult (643 chars):\n{\n  \"accepted\": true,\n  \"board\": {\n    \"cells\": [\n      \"X\",\n      null,\n      null,\n      \"O\",\n      \"O\",\n      \"X\",\n      \"X\",\n      \"O\",\n      null\n    ],\n    \"index_map\": [\n      \"0 top-left\",\n      \"1 top-middle\",\n      \"2 top-right\",\n      \"3 middle-left\",\n      \"4 center\",\n      \"5 middle-right\",\n      \"6 bottom-left\",\n      \"7 bottom-middle\",\n      \"8 bottom-right\"\n    ],\n    \"legal_moves\": [\n      1,\n      2,\n      8\n    ],\n    \"marks_by_index\": \"0: X, 1: empty, 2: empty, 3: O, 4: O, 5: X, 6: X, 7: O, 8: empty\",\n    \"status\": \"X to move\",\n    \"turn\": \"X\",\n    \"winner\": null\n  },\n  \"move\": {\n    \"cell\": 7,\n    \"mark\": \"O\"\n  }\n}"}]},{"role":"assistant","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":""}]},{"role":"assistant","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":"--- history[11] · rlm step · protocol_iteration 0 ---\n\nReasoning (3167 chars):\nCurrent board:\n0: X, 1: empty, 2: empty, 3: O, 4: O, 5: X, 6: X, 7: empty, 8: empty\n\nX . .\nO O X\nX . .\n\nLegal moves: [1, 2, 7, 8]\n\nO has 3 and 4. O can win by playing 5... wait, 5 is taken by X.\nO has 3 (middle-left) and 4 (center). To win, O needs 5 (middle-right) for the middle row, but X is at 5.\n\n\nLet me check the other winning lines for O. The middle column (1, 4, 7) has O at 4 with both 1 and 7 empty, so that's a potential threat. The diagonal through 4 (2, 4, 6) is blocked by X at 6. If O plays at 1 or 7, neither creates an immediate win on its own—O would need both squares to complete that column. Looking at X's position with 0, 5, and 6, X doesn't have any immediate winning threats since each potential line needs two more moves. So O should capitalize on the column 1 opportunity where O already has 4 and just needs to claim either 1 or 7 to set up the win.\n\nBut if O plays at either position, X can simply block the other. Let me explore whether O can create a fork instead—a position where O threatens to win in multiple ways simultaneously. If O plays at 2, that gives O the 2, 3, 4 cluster, but checking the resulting lines: row 0 gets blocked by X's 0, row 1 gets blocked by X's 5, and column 2 only has O at 2 so far.\n\nNow if O plays at 7 instead, O would have 3, 4, 7, which creates a real threat down column 1 at position 1. Similarly, playing at 1 gives O positions 1, 3, 4, threatening column 1 at position 7. So both moves create a single winning threat, but neither creates the fork I'm looking for. If O plays 1 and X blocks at 7, then O plays 8, O would have 1, 3, 4, 8 but the column 1 threat gets blocked and the diagonal doesn't work either. So this doesn't create a fork for O. Playing 7 gives O a threat in column 1 that needs just 1 to win. If X blocks there, I need to see what other winning opportunities open up for O. Playing 1 creates a threat on the 1-4-7 line. If X blocks at 7, I can follow up with 2 or 8 to look for a second winning threat, though the immediate options don't seem to guarantee a fork. O at 2,3,4,7 now, and I'm checking if there's a winning move by examining all possible lines. Looking through the board, none of the lines with O pieces give me two in a row with an open third spot—they're either blocked by X or don't have enough O's positioned to threaten a win.\n\nLet me try O at 8 instead to see if that creates better opportunities. 5 and 6 don't form a winning line either. O also has no immediate winning threats—the middle row is blocked by X at position 5, and there aren't any other dangerous combinations. So I need to focus on creating a fork. Playing at position 2 could set up column 1 as a threat, but let me think through what happens if O takes that move and whether it actually leads anywhere with optimal play from both sides.\n\nActually, let me evaluate each available move more carefully. If O plays at 1, that threatens the column 1 win. Playing at 7 also threatens column 1. Position 2 doesn't create any immediate threat, so I should go with 7 instead. That forces X to block at 1, and then I can reassess from there.O has a column-1 threat by playing 7 (forcing X to block 1).\n\nCode:\n```lashlang\nresult = await board.play({ cell: 7 })?\nsubmit \"I played bottom-middle — your turn!\"\n```\n\nFinal output:\n\"I played bottom-middle — your turn!\""}]},{"role":"user","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":"--- history[12] · user message · 29 chars ---\n\nI played X in the top middle."}]},{"role":"user","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":"--- history[13] · tool_call · play_move · ok · 0 ms ---\n\nArguments (15 chars):\n{\n  \"cell\": 2\n}\n\nResult (615 chars):\n{\n  \"accepted\": true,\n  \"board\": {\n    \"cells\": [\n      \"X\",\n      \"X\",\n      \"O\",\n      \"O\",\n      \"O\",\n      \"X\",\n      \"X\",\n      \"O\",\n      null\n    ],\n    \"index_map\": [\n      \"0 top-left\",\n      \"1 top-middle\",\n      \"2 top-right\",\n      \"3 middle-left\",\n      \"4 center\",\n      \"5 middle-right\",\n      \"6 bottom-left\",\n      \"7 bottom-middle\",\n      \"8 bottom-right\"\n    ],\n    \"legal_moves\": [\n      8\n    ],\n    \"marks_by_index\": \"0: X, 1: X, 2: O, 3: O, 4: O, 5: X, 6: X, 7: O, 8: empty\",\n    \"status\": \"X to move\",\n    \"turn\": \"X\",\n    \"winner\": null\n  },\n  \"move\": {\n    \"cell\": 2,\n    \"mark\": \"O\"\n  }\n}"}]},{"role":"assistant","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":""}]},{"role":"assistant","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":"--- history[15] · rlm step · protocol_iteration 0 ---\n\nReasoning (1147 chars):\nCurrent board:\n0: X, 1: X, 2: empty, 3: O, 4: O, 5: X, 6: X, 7: O, 8: empty\n\nX X .\nO O X\nX O .\n\nLegal moves: [2, 8]\n\nO needs to check for winning moves first:\n- O has 3, 4, 7\n- Check if O can win: 3-4-5? 5 is X. 3-6-9? No 9. 1-4-7? 1 is X. 7-8-9? No 9. \n\nWait, I need to be more systematic here. Let me scan through all the winning lines to see what's actually at stake. X has two in a row at positions 0 and 1, so X can win immediately by playing at 2. I should also check the columns and diagonals to see if there are other threats or opportunities.\n\nLooking at the diagonals, O has the center at 4, but neither diagonal is close to completion for O. The critical move is clear: O must block at position 2 to prevent X from winning on the next turn. After O blocks there, the board state shifts and I need to evaluate what happens next.\n\nWith only position 8 remaining as a legal move, X is forced to play there, filling the board completely. Checking all possible winning lines—rows, columns, and both diagonals—none of them form three in a row for either player. The game ends in a draw.X threatens to win at 2 (top-right). O must block there.\n\nCode:\n```lashlang\nresult = await board.play({ cell: 2 })?\nsubmit \"I blocked your win — your turn, one move left!\"\n```\n\nFinal output:\n\"I blocked your win — your turn, one move left!\""}]},{"role":"user","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":"--- history[16] · user message · 31 chars ---\n\nI played X in the bottom right.","cache_breakpoint":true}]},{"role":"user","blocks":[{"kind":"text","text":"\n\n\n=== CURRENT ITERATION: 1 ===\n\n\n=== FINALIZATION ===\n\nThe turn must finish through `submit <value>`. Prose alone does not end the turn.\n\n=== CONTEXT BUDGET ===\n\nTurn: 1 · Tokens: 7610 · frame switch threshold: 100000 (7%)."}]}],"tool_choice":"none","stream":false}}
{"schema_version":2,"id":"da43cb60-90b2-425e-a91f-b75f5a8c6a5a","timestamp":"2026-06-04T13:25:51.064416587+00:00","context":{"session_id":"68c950a0-f723-4516-9ab7-4b2d56ea1ec6","turn_id":"840984ca-b594-42d8-899c-3f30aff7c88f","turn_index":5,"protocol_iteration":0,"llm_call_id":"68c950a0-f723-4516-9ab7-4b2d56ea1ec6:5:0:0"},"type":"provider_stream_event","event":{"provider":"openai_compatible","sequence":0,"elapsed_ms":2,"event_name":"openai_compatible.request_body","raw_len":26280,"raw_sha256":"2c5c050e10e11003bea508da07bb77489666a4e2517837fc343da63e7ea2d4e2","raw_json":{"body":{"max_tokens":32768,"messages":[{"content":[{"cache_control":{"type":"ephemeral"},"text":"You are an AI coding assistant piloting the lash harness.\n\n## Execution\n\n**All actions go through `lashlang`.** Invoke documented operations with module syntax like `await agents.spawn({ ... })?` or `await web.search({ ... })?` from inside a fenced `lashlang` block. Start from operations listed under **Showcased Tools**; if a discovery tool is available, use it to find additional module call forms before calling them. Emit a block whenever you need to call an available operation or compute a value. Plain prose is for direct conversational replies that need no action.\n\n### `print` vs `submit`\n\n- `print <expr>` — inspect a value and keep going. Output appears on the next step and is capped: keep full tool results in variables and print only lengths, selected fields, samples, or slices. Don't print large objects just to hand-copy IDs back into code.\n- `submit <expr>` — final answer; ends the turn. Strings pass through as the reply; other values render as pretty JSON. If a **Required output** schema is present, the value must match it.\n\nNever `submit` a raw tool-result dump. If you need to look at something, `print` it, then `submit` a summary on a later step.\n\n### Turn shape\n\n**Exactly one ` ```lashlang ` fenced block per response.** Anything after the first block closes is dropped. Only ` ```lashlang ` is recognised — `rlm` and other labels are treated as plain prose.\n\n- Write small blocks. Each should do one focused step.\n- Keep prose around the block to one or two sentences of reasoning. Don't describe an action in prose instead of executing it.\n- After each result, decide: another block (more work), or finish.\n\nExample — inspect with an available operation, then submit:\n\n````\nChecking the available data.\n\n```lashlang\nresult = await web.search({ query: \"value\" })?\nprint { summary: slice(to_string(result), 0, 200) }\n```\n````\n\n…then on the next turn, once you've seen what you need:\n\n````\n```lashlang\nsubmit \"The bound version is 0.2.61.\"\n```\n````\n\n\n### Language\n\n- Values: null, booleans, numbers, strings, lists, records, and immutable `Image` handles. Literals: `[a, b]`, `{ a: 1, b: 2 }`.\n- Images: image-producing tools may return an `Image` value. Read metadata with `.id`, `.label`, `.size`, `.width`, `.height`; fields are read-only. `print(image)` or `print` on a list/record containing images sends both descriptor text and the actual image attachment to the next model call. `submit(image)`, `to_string(image)`, and JSON-like serialization emit only `{ \"type\": \"image\", \"id\": ..., \"label\": ..., \"size\": ..., \"width\": ..., \"height\": ... }`. `len(image)` is invalid; use `.size`.\n- Strings: `\"...\"` supports `\\n`, `\\r`, `\\t`, `\\\"`, and `\\\\`; `\"\"\"...\"\"\"` is multiline with the same escapes; `r\"\"\"...\"\"\"` and `r'''...'''` are raw multiline strings and preserve content exactly. Use raw multiline strings for JSON, Markdown, and other payloads with braces, backslashes, quotes, heredocs, or `@@` hunk markers.\n- Assign with `name = expr`. Variables persist across fenced blocks within the turn. You can also update mutable collection paths rooted at a variable: `record.field = value`, `record[key] = value`, `list[i] = value`, and nested forms like `state.groups[g].count = count + 1`. Record field/index assignment inserts or replaces fields; list assignment replaces an existing integer index only. Record indexing reads dynamic string-coerced keys and returns `null` when missing, so histogram code can use `counts[g] = counts[g] + 1`.\n- Module operations: call host capabilities through documented lowercase module paths, e.g. `await agents.spawn({ task: task })?`, `await web.search({ query: q })?`, or `await gmail.work.send({ to: to, body: body })?`. Host operations are awaited effects; pure UpperCamel value constructors shown in the Host Surface are ordinary expressions and must not be awaited. Bare calls are builtins only, not tools. `?` aborts the block with sanitized operation metadata if the operation fails.\n- Sleep: pause foreground code or process code with `sleep for \"5s\"` or `sleep until deadline`. Durations accept milliseconds, `ms`, `s`, `m`, or `h`; deadlines accept RFC3339 text or Unix epoch milliseconds.\n- Background processes: `process name(param: TYPE) { ... }` declares a reusable process definition. `handle = start name(param: value)` creates one process run from that definition and returns its run handle; trigger activations also create process runs. For account-parametric work, pass typed module authorities explicitly, e.g. `process notify(mail: Gmail) { await mail.send({ body: body })? finish true }` and `start notify(mail: gmail.work)`. For one-off concrete automations, a process body may reference concrete host paths such as `agents`, `web`, or `gmail.work` directly; params and locals shadow those captures. Inside a process use `yield value`, `wake value`, `finish value`, `fail value`, `payload = wait signal`, or `signal run handle with payload`. `wake value` emits a `process.wake` event that notifies the agent/session with `value`; use it when process progress, trigger output, or other background work should re-enter the model as context. `finish value` completes the run and stores `value` as the process success value. `fail value` completes it as failed; falling off the end is `finish null`. `submit` and `print` are foreground-only and invalid inside processes. `await handle` waits and returns a result wrapper like `{ ok: true, value: ... }`; when you need fields from the `finish` value, use `result = (await handle)?` and then read `result.field`. Cancel a live run with `cancel handle` (best-effort). If the Host Surface includes `processes.list`, use `await processes.list({})?` for running runs, `await processes.list({ definition: name })?` for runs of a definition, and `await processes.list({ status: \"any\" })?` for visible run history.\n- Execution labels: use `@label(title: \"Label\")` or `@label(title: \"Label\", description: \"Details\")` to name important Lashlang phases and graph steps. At top level, label meaningful setup, resource calls, submissions, branches, loops, or process declarations. Inside a `process` body, label durable steps such as awaited module calls, `start`, `sleep`, `wait signal`, `signal run`, `wake`, `yield`, `finish`, `fail`, `if`, loops, and setup statements that explain the process. Titles/descriptions must be string literals; do not use variables, interpolation, icons, colors, layout hints, or extra keys.\n- Independent operation fanout: call independent operations directly and store their values, e.g. `a = await web.search({ query: \"one\" })?` and `b = await files.read({ path: \"notes/two.md\" })?`. Use a named process for multi-step background work.\n- Control flow: statement `if`/`for`/`while`; `break` exits the nearest loop; `continue` skips to the nearest loop's next iteration; expression ternary `cond ? yes : no` (there is no expression-form `if`); boolean negation via `!cond` or `not cond`. Prefer bounded `while` loops where possible and bounded `for` loops over ranges/lists for fill or retry logic. `submit` is different from `break`: it ends the whole program/turn.\n- Bare expressions are valid statements in normal blocks.\n- When a **Bound Variables** section appears in the prompt, those names are already in scope inside lashlang blocks — read them directly instead of restating their values.\n\n### Host Surface\n\nAwaited runtime operations:\n\n- `await board.play(any)? -> any`\n- `await board.read(any)? -> any`\n- `await control.continue_as(any)? -> any`\n- `await triggers.cancel({ handle: TriggerHandle<any> })? -> bool`\n- `await triggers.list({ target: Process<any, any>?, name: str?, source_type: str?, enabled: bool? })? -> list[TriggerRegistration]`\n- `await triggers.register({ source: dict, target: Process<any, any>, inputs: dict, name: str? })? -> TriggerHandle<any>`\n\n### Builtins\n\nCall as functions (e.g. `len(x)`, `slice(s, 0, 200)`). For `slice`, `null` bounds mean start/end; negative bounds count from the end.\n\n- `len(x)` — length of string/list/record (0 for null); use `image.size` for images\n- `empty(x)` — true if length is 0\n- `slice(s, start, end)` — substring or sublist\n- `range(end)` / `range(start, end)` / `range(start, end, step)` — integer list, end-exclusive; positive or negative `step`, never `0`\n- `ceil_div(a, b)` / `floor_div(a, b)` — integer division helpers for chunk/count math; divisor must not be `0`\n- `push(list, item)` — new list with one item appended\n- `split(s, sep)` / `join(list, sep)` — string split/join\n- `find(s, needle, start?)` — zero-based character index of the first literal match, or `null`; `start` defaults to `0` and is a non-negative character index; an empty `needle` returns `start` when it is in bounds\n- `grep_text(s, needle)` — literal in-memory line search; `needle` must be non-empty; returns one record per matching line: `{ line: int, text: str, match: str, start: int, end: int }`, where `line` is 1-based, `text` is the line without its line ending, and `start`/`end` are zero-based character offsets within that line's `text` with `end` exclusive\n- `trim(s)` — strip whitespace\n- `starts_with(s, prefix)` / `ends_with(s, suffix)` / `contains(haystack, needle)`\n- `keys(record)` / `values(record)`\n- `to_string(x)` / `to_int(x)` / `to_float(x)`\n- `json_parse(s)` — parse a JSON string into a value\n- `format(template, arg0, arg1, ...)` — positional interpolation: `{}` auto-numbers, `{0}` / `{1}` pick a specific arg, `{{` / `}}` escape literal braces. Do not wrap args in a list: use `format(\"It is {}.\", trim(now.output))`, not `format(\"It is {}.\", [trim(now.output)])`.\n- `validate(value, Type { ... })` — check an intermediate value against a Type literal and return it unchanged, or abort with a validation error\n\n\n### Common patterns\n\nOperation-level errors are different from successful results that contain domain errors. `?` aborts the block only when the module operation itself failed:\n\n```lashlang\nprobe = await web.search({ query: \"value\" })?\nsubmit probe\n```\n\nBuild collections with explicit loops, not comprehensions:\n\n```lashlang\nitems = []\nfor key in [\"a\", \"b\"] {\n  value = await web.search({ query: key })?\n  items = push(items, { key: key, value: value })\n}\nsubmit items\n```\n\nPrint narrow observations. Keep large values in variables and print only keys, lengths, selected fields, or slices:\n\n```lashlang\nresult = await web.search({ query: \"value\" })?\ntext = to_string(result)\nprint { chars: len(text), head: slice(text, 0, 1200) }\n```\n\nFor multi-step work, inspect intermediate results before submitting success. Reaching `submit` ends the turn even mid-block:\n\n```lashlang\nfirst = await web.search({ query: \"value\" })?\nsecond = await web.fetch({ url: first[0].url })?\nif contains(to_string(second), \"needs_more_work\") {\n  print { first: first, second: second }\n} else {\n  submit second\n}\n```\n\n\n### Type literals\n\n`Type { field: shape, ... }` describes a record shape. Field separators are commas (trailing comma OK).\n\n- Scalars: `str`, `int`, `float`, `bool`, `dict`, `any`, `null`.\n- Collections: `list[shape]`, `enum[\"a\", \"b\"]`, nested `Type { ... }`.\n- **Optional field** — put `?` after the type: `email: str?` means the field may be absent from the record. If the field IS present, its value must be a string; `null` is **not** allowed.\n- **Nullable field** — use a union with `null`: `email: str | null` means the field is required and its value is either a string or null.\n- **Unions** — `a | b | c`, e.g. `status: str | int`, `value: str | null`.\n- Nested shapes require the `Type` keyword: `nested: Type { ok: bool }` (bare `{ ok: bool }` is rejected — that's a record value, not a type).\n\n```lashlang\nprofile = validate(record, Type { name: str, email: str?, tags: list[str] })\n```\n\n\n### Working with context\n\nYour turn's REPL trace is your working memory. Keep it small, decision-sized, and current. Big artifacts (files, search results, long pages, raw tool dumps) live outside — pull them in only when you need to compute over them yourself. Keep full results in variables; `print` only lengths, keys, selected fields, or slices, never large objects you intend to hand-copy IDs from.\n\nChoose the lightest mechanism that preserves progress:\n\n- Current variables already hold what you need → reason inline in lashlang.\n- Several independent operations are needed -> call each module operation and keep the values in variables; use a named `process` for multi-step background work.\n- The trace is bloated, stale, or failed attempts dominate -> use an available continuation tool to switch to a fresh AgentFrame with concrete state.\n- Anything tool-specific (parameters, return shapes, lifecycle) lives under **Showcased Tools** — don't infer a tool exists from these generic examples.\n\nExample fanout to two available operations (use `?` for fail-fast unwrapping):\n\n```lashlang\na = await web.search({ query: \"one\" })?\nb = await files.read({ path: \"notes/two.md\" })?\none = a\ntwo = b\nsubmit [one, two]\n```\n\n### Showcased Tools\n\n### await board.play({ cell: int >= 0 <= 8 })? -> record\nPlay one O move for the agent when it is O's turn. The move is a zero-based cell index: 0 top-left, 1 top-middle, 2 top-right, 3 middle-left, 4 center, 5 middle-right, 6 bottom-left, 7 bottom-middle, 8 bottom-right.\nParameters:\n- `cell: int >= 0 <= 8`\n\n### await board.read({})? -> record\nRead the app-owned Tic Tac Toe board. Returns the 0..8 index map, current marks by index, legal moves, winner, and whose turn it is.\n\n## Guidance\n\n- Be concise. Avoid filler, hedging, and performative tone.\n- Do not restate a conclusion you already stated. Once a fix location is identified, act on it in the same turn.\n- Prefer the simplest correct solution over cleverness or unnecessary abstraction.\n\n### Bound Variables\n\nThese variables are already bound in lashlang. Access them directly in fenced `lashlang` code; do not recreate them manually.\nType and size hints help you plan before inspecting a value.\n\nAvailable variables:\n- `history`: `list<HistoryItem>`, Readonly: true, projected binding, 13 entries\n\n## Environment\n\n### Tic Tac Toe Board\n\nYou are O. The human is X.\nCurrent turn: O.\nIndex map:\n0 top-left | 1 top-middle | 2 top-right\n3 middle-left | 4 center | 5 middle-right\n6 bottom-left | 7 bottom-middle | 8 bottom-right\nCurrent marks by index:\n0: X, 1: X, 2: O, 3: O, 4: O, 5: X, 6: X, 7: O, 8: X\nVisual board:\nX X O\nO O X\nX O X\nLegal moves: []\nStatus: draw.\nIf it is O's turn and the game is not over, call `board.play(...)` exactly once before answering. Only choose one of the legal move indexes. Use `board.read(...)` only when needed. Finish with `submit \"<one short user-facing sentence>\"`; do not repeat that sentence as prose outside the lashlang block. If your move ended the game, clearly say that you won or that the game ended in a draw; otherwise say it is the human's turn. Do not explain your strategy, do not describe threats, do not print an ASCII board, do not narrate every cell, and do not return JSON to the user.","type":"text"}],"role":"system"},{"content":"